The problem involves two parts. First, compute \(e = d - 1\) where \(d\) is the greatest common divisor of the distinct prime factors of 2021. Since \(2021 = 43 \times 47\), the distinct prime factors are 43 and 47, and their gcd is 1, so \(d = 1\) and \(e = 0\).

Next, maximize \(S = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{2^n} (a_1 a_2 \cdots a_n)^{1/n}\) subject to \(\sum_{k=1}^\infty a_k = 1\) and \(a_k \ge 0\). Using the method of Lagrange multipliers, the optimal sequence is a geometric progression \(a_k = c r^{k-1}\) with \(r = 1/4\) and \(c = 1 - r = 3/4\). Evaluating \(S\) for this sequence yields \(S = 2/3\). Numerical checks confirm that this is the maximum.

